postcontent:
Hello, I'm looking to load up on mags. Interested in AK47 and AR15 mags. Primarily interested in buying in bulk to make any traveling worth it. I don't need to buy in bulk, I'd buy just a few if the price was right, but I won't travel for it. If you happen to be able to meet me close to me then I'd buy even smaller quantities, but if I'm going to drive then it needs to be worth my effort. I strongly prefer that they be stock mags and not painted or whatever. 

Here's what I'm looking for:

AK 47: I'd be interested in pretty much any capacity, but THEY MUST BE STEEL. Not at all interested in the modern Korean mags. 

AR 15: primarily interested in 30rd mags, can be aluminum of polymer. No junk. 

Yes, I'd like to buy them at a discount. If I wanted to pay full price I'd buy from a retailer and have a warranty and have them shipped right to my door. But if you've got a pile of magazines laying around I may well be interested in taking them off your hands. I'm in the NE Valley but would consider traveling. Obviously the better the deal and the more mags involved the more willing I'd be to travel. 

Thanks for your time.

title: For Sale:  Colt Single Action Army Revolver SAA Gold, Frontier Six Shooter, Ivory Grips c.1925, Cased
postcontent:
This is a unique and extremely rare Colt Single Action Army revolver, in .44-40 caliber, which is factory gold plated with factory ivory grips, made in 1925 (serial #347526). It was originally shipped to G. W. Shroyer and Company, Dayton, Ohio, May 16, ’25, as a blue and case colored .32-20 with 7.5” barrel. It was returned to the Colt plant sometime between then and 1937, when it was changed to a Frontier Six Shooter (.44-40) with 5.5” barrel, ivory grips with medallions, and gold plated, as evidenced by the Colt rework “&” (ampersand) mark on the right rear of the trigger guard. It appears unfired since the factory rework.

As Kopec states in his book (p. 169, 1976 edition), “… in most parts of the world the SA’s hard working days were over, and … a number of its sales after 1923 were intended as gifts, presentations, prizes or just to rekindle memories of the ‘good old days.’…” This Colt typifies guns of that nature, remaining in 95% plus condition, with only the gold having been rubbed off in spots. The nickel finish, where the gold is missing, is almost perfect (gold plated guns had to be nickel plated before the gold would adhere).

This fine Colt has been custom cased in a late 1800’s lap desk, made of hardwoods and intricate inlaid veneers. It comes with the revolver’s accessories as well as antique pen, nibs and brass ink well holders. The case also has its key and locks.

The size of these plate carrier vests are adjustable from "Small to X-Large"
MIL-A-46100 steel is Military spec armor. MIL-A 46100 armor is used to stop high velocity projectiles (HVPs). This particular grade military spec armor steel is especially useful to protect structures or vehicles from sniper fire or any form of weapon that will emit the HVPs depending on the threat level, various thicknesses of steel may be required to protect vital organs.
The measurement of the plates are both
1/4" and .393" also not to mention tested by the US Army test labs.
I had ar500 plates but 46100 material is by far a lot better. Some people say AR500 are military steel but the military never uses ar500. I used a .308 rifle and a .223 at these plates at 36 and 50 yards. Then shot it with AK 47 50rnds, 5.56 30rnds, endless .357/9mm/45cal, 7.62x54R, .30-06 and a 300 win mag 3 times at 250yards, that did flatten the plate but still no penetration. Not to mention shot at it with a .45 handgun...still no penetration. This will not fail to disappoint as it this is one of the best quality steel out there. Ar500 is target material not to be used as body armor. This body armor with the 2 plates and the vest weighs a total of 12 pounds. I've shot at this multiple times with different rifles and Handguns and it still holds up. You could attach MOLLE gear to this vest such as your Hydration water Carrier, Rifle and Handgun Magazine pouches, Radio pouches, EMT Medical pouches and etc.

If you want the entire Front/Back & Side set with the carrier vest, 2 side plates, Front and back plates that would be $300.00

I am mostly looking to get educated on these caliber's. I don't know any thing about them.
it appears to be pistol ammo, but I have no idea, again the head stamps say 41 cal and 42 cal.

if you are interested in them, I may or may not be willing to trade, deal, barter, sell, etc, but not entirely sure yet. I need to determine my fcats and values.

any help any of you can share with me would be fantastic
any links, or any storys of experience, etc.

I hope to post a pic soon. thank you to each of you reads and or responds for your very valuable time in advance. I appreciate the help.

title: For Sale:  german WWII flare gun made by Schneide AG, Leipzig
postcontent: Made to save precious war materials and production effort, the LP42 is made out of stamped steel or zinc in the white.  There were two manufacturers for this pistol.  Schneide AG, Leipzig pistols are marked "wa" and the poorer quality C&W Meinel-Scholer of Sachsen are marked "eug."  This was a simpler design that was not prone to breakage like the Heeres Model.  This pistol too had brown to black bakalite grips and there will be waffenamts on the rear of the breach.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mosin 91/30 Good shape: Russian w/Bayo & Pouches
location: New Albany area, Indiana, United States
postcontent:
Near New Albany: For sale or trade, Russian Mosin 91/30. With bayonet and pouches and oil can. I'm figuring the numbers do not match. The original numbers are all replaced with etched numbers, in the steel. But the new etched numbers DO ALL MATCH on all components. I read on the Web that after the rifles were captured/surrendered, back in the war, they were then disassembled then put back together (at a later date) in a random order and the newly assembled parts were re-numbered (via etching on the steel) after assembly. This may or may not be true, but I read it in several different places.

title: For Sale:  SOLD - 1891/30 Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
This is a very nice Russian 1891/30 Mosin Nagant in 7.62x54 cal.  This rifle has matching numbers, and the stock cartouche is clearly visible.  The bolt was modified to be a flat bolt, and the receiver was originally drilled for a scope mount, and those holes have been filled.

The Mosin Nagant rifles were developed at Tula by Sergi Mosin.  The feed system was developed by Belgian designer Leon Nagant.  Russian production began in 1892 and took place at the Imperial ordnance factories at Tula, Sestroryetsk nd Izhevsk.  The Model 1891 is a 7.62x54R mm bolt action rifle with a 31.6 inch bbl, a 5 shot integral magazine, and a ladder rear sight.  The weight of these rifles is about 9.5 lbs and they were used extensively in the Russo-Japanese war of 1904-1905.  This is a very nice example of that rifle.
